Ensure Jenkins has Docker and Kubernetes CLI (kubectl) installed and configured to communicate with your Docker Desktop Kubernetes cluster.

Create a file named Jenkinsfile in the root of your repository:


pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Checkout') {
            steps {
                // Pulls the latest code from your GitHub repository
                checkout scm
            }
        }

        stage('Build Docker Image') {
            steps {
                script {
                    echo 'Building Docker Image...'
                    // Builds the image using the Dockerfile
                    sh 'docker build -t restaurant-menu:latest .'
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy to Kubernetes') {
            steps {
                script {
                    echo 'Deploying to Kubernetes Cluster...'
                    // Apply deployment and service
                    sh 'kubectl apply -f k8s/deployment.yaml'
                    sh 'kubectl apply -f k8s/service.yaml'
                    
                    // Restart the deployment to ensure the latest image is pulled
                    sh 'kubectl rollout restart deployment restaurant-menu-deployment'
                }
            }
        }
    }
}




Final Deployment Steps:
Commit the Jenkinsfile to GitHub.

In Jenkins, create a new Pipeline project.

Under the Pipeline section, select Pipeline script from SCM, choose Git, and input your repository URL.

Set the script path to Jenkinsfile.

Run the build.

Visualizing in Docker Desktop:
Once Jenkins finishes executing the pipeline successfully, open Docker Desktop. If you have the Kubernetes extension enabled, you can navigate to the Kubernetes tab to see your restaurant-menu-deployment pods running. You can view the live site by opening your browser and navigating to http://localhost:30080.
